Jeb! was unenthusiastic from the get.  Trump had that one right, Jeb! lacks oomph.  If you're trying to get people to support your candidacy, the very least you can do is act like you're excited about it.

Jeb! reminds me of a girl at a fraternity "pig party," where the object is to see who can bring the ugliest girl to the party.  Jeb! looks like he just realized why his date won.

He's like a guy who lost his advertising job and found himself greeting shoppers at a Walmart in Kentucky.

Reluctantly throwing his hat into the ring, Jeb! couldn't seem to define the nature of his candidacy or what it was he wanted to accomplish.  He had nothing to say until he started answering a few of Trump's verbal jabs.

The first question Jeb! faced, one he should have anticipated for the last seven years, was whether or not he thought his brother, GW Bush made the right choice invading Iraq.

The question was phrased very specifically and gave Jeb! the gift of something his brother didn't have, hindsight.

The question was, knowing what we know now, would he still support the invasion of Iraq.  It was a leading question, giving Jeb! the benefit of twelve years of history upon which to base his response.

He wasn't even asked if would have made that decision with only the knowledge we had back in 2003.  Jeb! was asked to make that decision with full knowledge that there were no weapons of mass destruction, that the fall of Saddam Hussein would lead to the rise of ISIS and that an invasion of Iraq would lead to an interminable military entanglement.

After three days of deliberation, Jeb! proclaimed his support of his brother's decision. Apparently, blood is thicker than common sense.

Another of Jeb's heroic figures turns out to be Michigan Governor, Rick Snyder.  Jeb! says he admires the way Snyder took responsibility for the water problem in Flint.  In case you haven't heard about it, you can read about it <a href="http://www.cnn.com/2016/01/11/health/toxic-tap-water-flint-michigan/">here</a>.

Snyder taking responsibility for poisoning the water in Flint, Michigan is like Hitler taking responsibility for the Holocaust.  Of course he's responsible, he did it.

First, Snyder declared a State of Emergency in Flint, allowing the State of Michigan to take control away from Flint's elected officials.  That miracle was brought to you by the (Republican) geniuses in the Michigan legislature

Then they switched Flint's water supply from Lake Huron to the Flint River and sold the supply pipes to a private vendor.

70 miles from America's Great Lakes and nothing but toxic water coming from every faucet in Flint, MI.  Even <a href="http://www.mlive.com/news/flint/index.ssf/2015/10/gm.html">General Motors refused to use the water from the Flint River</a> because it was corroding engine parts.

And that, my friends is who Jeb! Bush admires.  Some aspiration for a presidential candidate.

We're not even going to mentioned Mama Bush (Barbara) being called in to defend her son against The Donald's onslaught.  We're not going to mention that when first asked, she said that she "thought Jeb! <em>might</em> make a good president."

Not exactly a ringing endorsement from your mother.

We're going to wind up here with Jeb's latest ad campaign, first previewed up there in New Hampshire.  (Raise your hand if you can point to New Hampshire on a map)

Jeb's newest campaign shows him with his brother, George, who reassures us that Jeb! will keep America safe.

A man considered to be one of the worst presidents ever, who presided over both the attack on 9/11 and one of the worst recessions in our history, a man who started two wars with no exit strategy, who did more to destabilize the Middle East than any terrorist organization you can name and can not pronounce the word "nuclear" is telling us that his brother will keep us safe.

What happened, Clint Eastwood refuse to make the pitch?

