To his credit, Rubio seemed better able to control his dry mouth this year, but the lip smacking is still pretty off putting.  Hopefully, AstraZeneca has a pill for that.

If you're not a hard core political junkie, you can look at Rubio's victory speech this way;  it was equivalent to Benedict Cumberbatch giving an acceptance speech for the Best Actor award at last year's Academy Awards (Eddie Redmayne won).

Rubio's jubilation seemed out of place for a third place finish.  It was almost as if he was surprised that anyone at all voted for him.  Someone on his staff should've told Rubio that he was beat out by a guy who had never had his name on any ballot, anywhere, ever.

Rubio's speech began, "So this is the moment they said would never happen.  For months, for months they told us we had no chance."

That was a bad start.  Pundits from MSNBC to CNN to Fox News have all been predicting a Rubio surge for months.  We can chalk that up to youthful inexperience.  A more seasoned politician knows how to bury lies amidst smidgens of truth.

Rubio went on to say, "...the people of this great state have sent a very clear message. After seven years of Barack Obama, we are not waiting any longer to take our country back. "

This one's a real head scratcher.  It sounds like Rubio's saying something big here, but I can't, for the life of me figure out what.

Consider the following:
1.  Everyone who cast a vote in the Iowa Republican caucus was a Republican.
2.  All of Rubio's opponents in the Iowa Republican caucus were Republicans
3.  Barack Obama was not represented on the floor of any of the Iowa Republican caucuses.

How then, did any of Rubio's 43,165 votes say anything about Barack Obama or taking our country back?  (It's never clear exactly who is doing the taking and from whom they are taking it.)

I get that Rubio is trying to tie Hillary Clinton to Barack Obama, but he acts like he's running against the President, not the former First Lady.

That strategy worked pretty well in the 2008 election because tying the Republican candidates to the dismal presidency of G.W. Bush was both easy and deadly.

It remains to be seen if tying Hillary Clinton to a presidency that, by all metrics and benchmarks was successful, especially one that succeeded a worldwide economic collapse.

Either way, those 43,165 votes weren't cast against Barack Obama, they were cast against Ted Cruz, Donald Trump, Carly Fiorina, et cetera.

Heck, with that lineup, it's pretty easy to cast a vote against any of them.  Two of the eleven who participated in the Iowa Republican caucus should be euthanized on general principles.

Most of the speech is a mish mash of 2nd Amendment fear mongering, Divine selection, military machismo and carefully crafted biographic mumbo jumbo.

Rubio's speech is also peppered with code phrases and conflicted images like, "...families struggling to raise their children with the right values."  What are the "right values" and who makes that call?

He talks about the president defending the Constitution, but has made it clear that God's law is above man's law.  In other words, he'll defend the Constitution when it suits his religious views.

Rubio, like many of his cohorts are quick to assert "that our rights come from our creator."  While there is a constitutional reference to "the Creator" as being the source of our rights, the president should only be concerned with those rights conferred upon us by the Constitution itself and clarified by justices charged with interpreting the Founders words.

Even when those rights conflict with her personal, religious beliefs.  Enforcing fundamental interpretations of God's law is best left to those most qualified, like the Supreme Leader of Iran and the Taliban.

Donald Trump reprised his role as birther by questioning Ted Cruz's eligibility to be president, just as he did with Barack Obama.

In case you haven't heard, Ted Cruz was born in Canada.

I question Marco Rubio's eligibility to be president, and not because his parents didn't become citizens until after little baby Marco was born.  (What, you didn't know that Marco was an anchor baby?)

I question Marco Rubio's eligibility to be president because I'm not sure on what planet he was born.

